            "plan": "## Context: PR #11015 as it stands today\n\n**What it does:**\n1. CLI sends `model: 'auto'` + `x-api-provider: auto` on every Anthropic LLM call.\n2. The proxy route (`apps/backend/src/app/api/llm/a/v1/messages/route.ts`) intercepts every request, calls `anthropicModelRouter.route()`, which calls a Fireworks-hosted classifier (50 ms timeout, rule-based fallback).\n3. Routing decision rewrites the body's `model`, picks `apiProvider`, and returns response with `x-resolved-model` header.\n4. CLI reads the header and exposes it via `onResolvedModel`.\n\n**What's wrong vs the goals you stated:**\n- Routing happens on **every** turn, baked into the proxy. The agent has no agency: every API call pays the latency, and we cannot decide \"only first turn\" or \"only sub-agents\" without changing the proxy.\n- The interface is hard-coded to one Anthropic route — not a sharable abstraction the CLI, evals, or other proxies can reuse.\n- The classifier signals (`lastUserMessage`, `recentToolCalls`, `hasImages`, `turnCount`) are extracted from the request body inside the proxy and miss the signals you want (sub-agent? exec mode? root vs nested?).\n- There is no offline harness — `classifyTurn` directly calls `fetch`/`getFireworksApiKeySecret`, so you can't run it on a JSON file of fixtures.\n- The \"effective model\" is computed per call and never persisted, so the agent can't \"lock in\" a model for a session.\n\n---\n\n## Proposal\n\nRefactor the routing system into five well-separated layers, with one explicit API call from the agent and pluggable strategies on both client and server. The PR's existing classifier prompt, rule-based fallback, and metrics stay; only the wiring changes.\n\n### 1. New `@factory/model-router` package (shared between CLI and backend)\n\nA new workspace package (or `packages/utils/src/model-router/`) that owns the **interface** and **pure logic** with zero runtime dependencies on Next.js, Fireworks, AWS secrets, or React. This is 