el: { modelId: string; apiProvider: ApiProvider; expiresAt: number } | null = null;\n\npublic getEffectiveAutoModel(): typeof this.effectiveAutoModel { ... }\npublic setEffectiveAutoModel(decision: RoutingDecision): void { /* persist to session settings */ }\n```\n\nThe model is **persisted to session settings** so resumes and sub-agents inherit it. When the user selects \"auto\" in the model selector, the CLI calls `selectModel(...)` once, picks `options[0]`, stores it, and uses it as the actual model for subsequent LLM calls — no more `model: 'auto'` going to the proxy.\n\nThe proxy route loses its router import and the `wasAutoRouted` branch entirely (~50 lines deleted from `messages/route.ts`).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Improvement #2 — Flexible \"when to route\" policy\n\nA `RoutingPolicy` decides whether *this turn* should consult the selector. It lives in the shared package and is configured per surface.\n\n```ts\n// packages/utils/src/model-router/policy.ts\nexport interface RoutingPolicyContext {\n  surface: SessionSurface;\n  isSubAgent: boolean;\n  turnNumber: number;        // 0-indexed within the session\n  effectiveModelAge: number; // ms since last decision, Infinity if none\n  hasEffectiveModel: boolean;\n}\n\nexport interface RoutingPolicy {\n  shouldRoute(ctx: RoutingPolicyContext): boolean;\n}\n\n// Composable building blocks:\nexport const onceAtTurn   = (n: number): RoutingPolicy => ({ shouldRoute: c => c.turnNumber === n });\nexport const everyTurn    : RoutingPolicy = { shouldRoute: () => true };\nexport const onlyForSurface = (s: SessionSurface): RoutingPolicy => ({ shouldRoute: c => c.surface === s });\nexport const orPolicies   = (...ps: RoutingPolicy[]): RoutingPolicy => ({ shouldRoute: c => ps.some(p => p.shouldRoute(c)) });\nexport const andPolicies  = (...ps: RoutingPolicy[]): RoutingPolicy => ({ shouldRoute: c => ps.every(p => p.shouldRoute(c)) });\nexport const expireAfter  = (ms: number): RoutingPolicy => ({ shouldRoute: c => c.effectiveModel