=> `\"${c.modelId}\"`).join(', ');\n\n  return [\n    'You are a task routing classifier for the Factory AI coding agent.',\n    'Every turn you are given: (1) a fixed list of candidate models and',\n    '(2) context about the user\\'s current turn. Score each candidate with',\n    'the probability that it can complete the turn SUCCESSFULLY with',\n    'MINIMAL BACK-AND-FORTH OR ERROR. You are not allowed to pick a',\n    'winner yourself — the downstream selector will handle cost/quality',\n    'tradeoffs using your scores.',\n    '',\n    '# Candidate models',\n    '',\n    candidateBlocks,\n    '',\n    '# Scoring rubric',\n    '',\n    'For each candidate, emit a score in the [0.0, 1.0] range:',\n    '',\n    '- 1.0 — Will almost certainly solve the task on the first attempt.',\n    '- 0.9 — Very likely to solve it cleanly.',\n    '- 0.8 — Likely success; minor follow-up edits possible.',\n    '- 0.7 — Borderline; acceptable but may need a nudge. This is the',\n    `  QUALITY_THRESHOLD (${QUALITY_THRESHOLD}) the selector uses to decide`,\n    '  whether cheaper models are viable.',\n    '- 0.5 — Coin-flip; expect rework.',\n    '- 0.3 — Likely to miss the spec or thrash.',\n    '- 0.0 — Hard reject (cannot complete; e.g. image-only tasks on a',\n    '  text-only model). Hard rejects MUST be 0.0 exactly.',\n    '',\n    'Scoring heuristics (use them in this order):',\n    '',\n    '1. Hard capability gates first. If a candidate lacks image support',\n    '   and the turn has images, score it 0.0.',\n    '2. Reward cheap models on simple work. A 0.9 for MiniMax on a',\n    '   single-file edit is better than 0.95 for Opus — Opus is still a',\n    '   viable fallback because its score will also be high.',\n    '3. Penalize cheap models on complex work. Multi-file refactors,',\n    '   architecture decisions, subtle debugging, and error recovery',\n    '   usually warrant 0.3-0.5 on MiniMax-class models and 0.9+ on Opus.',\n    '4. Long reasoning chains (step-by-step debugging, plan-then-execute)',\n    '   favor the stronger model.',\n    '5. Read-only / Q&A turns (Grep, Read, LS, short questions) are',\n    '   cheap-model territory — score 0.85-0.95 for MiniMax.',\n    '6. Turns that already show failed tool calls or error recovery in',\n    '   the history lean complex; bias toward Opus.',\n    '7. Be conservative when unsure. If in doubt between 0.6 and 0.8,',\n    '   pick 0.6 for the cheap model and 0.9 for the strong one.',\n    '',\n    '# Output contract',\n    '',\n    'Respond with a single JSON object and nothing else. The JSON MUST',\n    'have exactly this shape:',\n    '',\n    '{',\n    '  \"scores\": {',\n    `    ${modelIdsJson.split(', ').map((id) => `${id}: <number between 0.0 and 1.0>`).join(',\\n    ')}`,\n    '  },',\n    '  \"classification\": \"TRIVIAL\" | \"STANDARD\" | \"COMPLEX\",',\n    '  \"reasoning\": \"<1 short sentence>\"',\n    '}',\n    '',\n    '- Include an entry in `scores` for EVERY candidate id listed above.',\n    '- `classification` is a coarse bucket used for telemetry only.',\n    '- `reasoning` is optional but helps debug routing decisions.',\n    '- Do not include any markdown, code fences, or prose outside the',\n    '  JSON object.',\n    '- Do not use chain-of-thought; respond with the JSON directly.',\n  ].join('\\n');\n}\n\n/**\n * Build the dynamic \"task signals\" user prompt. Contains only per-turn\n * data so the static system prompt can stay perfectly cacheable.\n *\n * Truncates the longest free-form field (`lastUserMessage`) to the\n * computed budget so the total input stays under\n * DYNAMIC_SUFFIX_MAX_TOKENS.\n */\nexport function buildDynamicTaskUserPrompt(\n  signals: ClassifierSignals\n): string {\n  const fixedLines: string[] = [\n    `turn_number: ${signals.turnCount}`,\n    `surface: ${signals.surface}`,\n    `sub_agent: ${signals.isSubAgentSession ? 'yes' : 'no'}`,\n    `images_present: ${signals.hasImages ? 'yes' : 'no'}`,\n  ];\n\n  const toolCallsSlice = signals.recentToolCalls.slice(-MAX_RECENT_TOOL_CALLS);\n  const toolCallsStr =\n    toolCallsSlice.length > 0\n      ? toolCallsSlice.map((tc) => `${tc.name}:${tc.status}`).join(', ')\n      : 'none';\n  fixedLines.push(`recent_tool_calls: ${toolCallsStr}`);\n\n  const hasErrors =\n    signals.hasFailedToolCalls ??\n    signals.recentToolCalls.some((tc) => tc.status === 'error');\n  fixedLines.push(`has_failed_tool_calls: ${hasErrors ? 'yes' : 'no'}`);\n\n  if (signals.conversationSummary) {\n    const summaryBudget = 800; // chars, leaves room for message\n    const summary =\n      signals.conversationSummary.length > summaryBudget\n        ? `${signals.conversationSummary.slice(0, summaryBudget)}... [truncated]`\n        : signals.conversationSummary;\n    fixedLines.push(`conversation_summary: ${summary}`);\n  }\n\n  // Reserve room for everything above, then truncate the user message\n  // to fit the remaining budget. We use conservative char/token ratios.\n  const fixedText = fixedLines.join('\\n');\n  const fixedTokens = estimateTokenCount(fixedText);\n  const messageTokenBudget = Math.max(\n    200,\n    DYNAMIC_SUFFIX_MAX_TOKENS - fixedTokens - 200 // 200 tokens of slack\n  );\n  const messageCharBudget = Math.min(\n    MAX_MESSAGE_LENGTH,\n    messageTokenBudget * CHARS_PER_TOKEN_ESTIMATE\n  );\n\n  const rawMessage = signals.lastUserMessage.trim();\n  const truncatedMessage =\n    rawMessage.length > messageCharBudget\n      ? `${rawMessage.slice(0, messageCharBudget)}\\n... [truncated ${rawMessage.length - messageCharBudget} chars]`\n      : rawMessage;\n\n  return [\n    '# Turn context',\n    '',\n    fixedText,\n    '',\n    '# User message',\n    '',\n    truncatedMessage || '[empty]',\n    '',\n    'Score each candidate model per the rubric above. Respond with JSON only.',\n  ].join('\\n');\n}\n",
