iculty, not simplicity.\"\n\n**Layer 2 — Model Capability Cards (per-model, structured, data-rich)**\n\nEach model gets a self-contained XML card. The card has a fixed schema that every model must fill, so adding model #8 is the same work as model #2. No card references any other model — each stands alone.\n\nThe card schema:\n\n```xml\n<model id=\"model-id-here\">\n  <image_support>yes|no</image_support>\n  <strengths>\n    2-3 sentences: what task shapes this model reliably solves.\n    Written as falsifiable claims, not marketing.\n  </strengths>\n  <weaknesses>\n    2-3 sentences: what task shapes cause this model to fail.\n    These are the red flags that should push the score toward 0.3.\n  </weaknesses>\n  <examples>\n    <example verdict=\"pass\" score=\"0.85\">\n      <task>Fix the off-by-one error in binary_search.py and add a test</task>\n      <why>Single-file edit with clear scope; model handles this cleanly</why>\n    </example>\n    <example verdict=\"fail\" score=\"0.35\">\n      <task>Find the deleted secret in the repo history and clean it up</task>\n      <why>Forensic git recovery requires careful multi-step reasoning across reflog/fsck; model tends to try simple grep and give up</why>\n    </example>\n    ... up to 20 examples ...\n  </examples>\n</model>\n```\n\nThe few-shot examples are the most powerful lever. Each example is a task description + a verdict (pass/fail from real eval data) + a short `why` explaining the failure mode or success pattern. These examples are what teach the classifier to distinguish \"sounds simple but is hard\" from \"actually simple.\"\n\nThe examples should be balanced: ~10 pass + ~10 fail per model. The fail examples are more important because they teach the classifier *when to score low*, which is exactly the calibration gap we observed. The fail examples should be drawn directly from the headroom data — tasks where the model has <30% pass rate despite the prompt sounding tractable.\n\n**Layer 3 — Task Prompt (