re cost and latency entirely; judge capability only.',\n    '',\n    '# Candidate models',\n    '',\n    candidateBlocks,\n    '',\n    '# Scoring rubric',\n    '',\n    'For each candidate, emit a score in the [0.0, 1.0] range:',\n    '',\n    '- 1.0 — Will almost certainly solve the task on the first attempt.',\n    '- 0.9 — Very likely to solve it cleanly.',\n    '- 0.8 — Likely success; minor follow-up edits possible.',\n    `- 0.7 — Borderline; acceptable but may need a nudge. This is the`,\n    `  QUALITY_THRESHOLD (${QUALITY_THRESHOLD}) the selector uses to`,\n    '  decide whether cheaper models are viable.',\n    '- 0.5 — Coin-flip; expect rework.',\n    '- 0.3 — Likely to miss the spec or thrash.',\n    '- 0.0 — Hard reject (cannot complete; e.g. image-only tasks on a',\n    '  text-only model). Hard rejects MUST be exactly 0.0.',\n    '',\n    'Scoring heuristics (apply in order):',\n    '',\n    '1. Hard capability gates first. If a candidate lacks image support',\n    '   and the turn has images, score it 0.0.',\n    '2. Reward weaker models on simple work. A 0.9 for a small model on',\n    '   a single-file edit is better than 0.95 for the flagship — the',\n    '   flagship is still a viable fallback because its score will be',\n    '   high too.',\n    '3. Penalize weaker models on complex work: multi-file refactors,',\n    '   architecture decisions, subtle debugging, and error recovery',\n    '   usually warrant 0.3-0.5 on standard-tier models and 0.9+ on',\n    '   premium-tier models.',\n    '4. Long reasoning chains (step-by-step debugging, plan-then-',\n    '   execute) favor the strongest model available.',\n    '5. Read-only / Q&A turns (Grep, Read, LS, short questions) are',\n    '   cheap-model territory — score 0.85-0.95 for standard models.',\n    '6. Turns that already show failed tool calls or error recovery in',\n    '   the history lean complex; bias toward the premium model.',\n    '7. Be conservative when unsure. If in doubt between 