            "content": "# Model Router: Engineering Notes & Knowledge Base\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. [System Architecture](#system-architecture)\n2. [Classifier Design](#classifier-design)\n3. [Prompt Engineering Philosophy](#prompt-engineering-philosophy)\n4. [Cost-Weighted Selector](#cost-weighted-selector)\n5. [Candidate Registry & Model Cards](#candidate-registry--model-cards)\n6. [Offline Evaluation Framework](#offline-evaluation-framework)\n7. [Production Evaluation (TB2)](#production-evaluation-tb2)\n8. [Infrastructure & Deployment](#infrastructure--deployment)\n9. [Results & Quality Analysis](#results--quality-analysis)\n10. [Known Failure Patterns](#known-failure-patterns)\n11. [Operational Runbook](#operational-runbook)\n\n---\n\n## 1. System Architecture\n\n### Design Principles\n\n- **Agent-driven, not proxy-based**: The router runs in-process inside the droid binary (CLI or backend), NOT as a middleware proxy. The agent explicitly calls the router before each LLM turn.\n- **Single implementation, two surfaces**: The same `Router` class from `@factory/droid-core/model-router` runs identically in the CLI (`apps/cli/src/models/modelRouter.ts`) and the backend (`apps/backend/src/app/api/llm/router/select-model/route.ts`).\n- **Graceful degradation**: If `OPENAI_API_KEY` is unavailable, the router returns `null` and the caller falls back to Opus. No crash, no error — just a log warning and full-quality service.\n- **Prompt-cache optimized**: The classifier prompt is split into a static system prefix (model cards + scoring theory) and a dynamic user suffix (session context). The static prefix hits OpenAI's automatic prompt cache on subsequent calls within the same session.\n\n### Code Locations\n\n| Component | Path |\n|-----------|------|\n| Router class | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/router.ts` |\n| Classifier | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/classifiers/gpt5-mini.ts` |\n| Prompt builder | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/classifiers/prompt.ts` |\n| Selector | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/selector.ts` |\n| Candidates registry | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/candidates.ts` |\n| Signal extraction | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/signals.ts` |\n| Context packing | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/context.ts` |\n| Types | `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/types.ts` |\n| CLI integration | `apps/cli/src/models/modelRouter.ts` |\n| Eval harness | `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/run.ts` |\n| Eval fixtures | `evals/router/headroom-fixtures.jsonl` |\n| Selector optimizer | `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/optimize-selector.ts` |\n\n### Data Flow\n\n```\nUser message arrives\n  → buildClassifierSignalsFromHistory() extracts signals\n  → Router.route(signals) called\n    → Gpt5MiniTaskClassifier.classify(signals, candidates)\n      → buildStaticClassifierSystemPrompt(candidates) [cached]\n      → buildDynamicTaskUserPrompt(signals) [per-turn]\n      → POST api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions (GPT-5.4-mini)\n      → Parse structured JSON: { scores: { model_id: float }, reasoning: string }\n    → CostWeightedSelector.select(scores, candidates)\n      → Apply utility formula: utility(c) = score - α·score^(1+γ)·relative_cost\n      → Return highest-utility candidate\n  → RoutingDecision returned to caller\n  → Caller uses routed model for the LLM call\n```\n\n### Key Constraint: Direct OpenAI Access\n\nThe classifier calls `api.openai.com` directly — NOT through the Factory LLM proxy. This is because the proxy rejects requests whose messages don't include the canonical droid system prompt. The classifier uses its own specialized prompt, so it must bypass the proxy.\n\nThis means:\n- A raw `OPENAI_API_KEY` env var is required wherever the router runs\n- In the CLI: reads from `process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY`\n- In the backend: fetches from AWS Secrets Manager (`OPEN_AI_API_KEY` in us-west-1)\n- In eval workers: fetched by the daemon from `PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY` in us-west-1, then passed through to Docker containers via `_SECRET_ENV_KEYS`\n\n---\n\n## 2. Classifier Design\n\n### Model Choice: GPT-5.4-mini\n\nWe use GPT-5.4-mini with `reasoning_effort='low'` for classification. This was chosen because:\n- Fast (~2.3s median latency)\n- Cheap (negligible cost vs the tasks it routes)\n- Structured output support (JSON schema enforcement)\n- Prompt caching (static prefix cached across calls)\n\n### Configuration\n\n- **No temperature parameter**: OpenAI rejects `temperature` when combined with `reasoning_effort`. We tested `seed` for determinism but reasoning models are inherently non-deterministic (35.7% variance with seed). Final config: `reasoning_effort='low'` only.\n- **Structured output**: We pass a JSON schema via OpenAI's `response_format` with `strict: true`. The schema is dynamically generated per candidate list (model IDs become required properties of the `scores` object).\n\n### Output Format\n\n```json\n{\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"claude-opus-4-6\": 0.85,\n    \"kimi-k2.5\": 0.35\n  },\n  \"reasoning\": \"This task requires sustained debugging of a compiler's GC...\"\n}\n```\n\n### Variance Characteristics\n\nFrom 75-fixture, 3-trial offline eval:\n- Mean score σ for Opus: 0.032\n- Mean score σ for Kimi: 0.044\n- Unstable fixtures (routing flips across trials): 10.7%\n- These are irreducible — reasoning models don't support deterministic mode\n\n---\n\n## 3. Prompt Engineering Philosophy\n\n### Three-Layer Architecture\n\nThe classifier prompt has three layers, each with a distinct purpose:\n\n1. **Scoring Theory (Layer 1)**: Model-agnostic calibration guide. Defines what scores mean (0.0–1.0 probability scale), how to reason about tasks, and how to handle uncertainty. Never references any model by name.\n\n2. **Model Cards (Layer 2)**: Per-candidate capability data. Each card is self-contained with: capabilities, strengths, weaknesses, and scored examples drawn from real evaluation data. Cards are the ONLY place model-specific information lives.\n\n3. **Task Prompt (Layer 3)**: Dynamic per-turn session context wrapped in XML, followed by a scoring instruction.\n\n### Four Immutable Rules (enforced in code comment block)\n\n1. **MODEL-AGNOSTIC SCORING**: The rubric never references any model by name. Per-model context lives ONLY in the cards.\n2. **N-MODEL READY**: Works identically with 2 or 8 candidates. No binary-choice logic.\n3. **DENSE MODEL CARDS**: Self-contained, flat structure. Up to 20 scored examples per card, balanced between strengths and weaknesses. Every example must have high information gain.\n4. **HONEST UNCERTAINTY**: Short prompts don't mean easy tasks. Absence of visible complexity is itself a signal of possible hidden difficulty.\n\n### Anti-Overfitting Principles\n\n- Model cards describe **general patterns**, not task names (\"multi-step workflows with feedback loops\" not \"train-fasttext\")\n- Weakness categories are broad (\"algorithms requiring sustained reasoning\") with parenthetical examples\n- Score examples use generic task descriptions, never TB2 task IDs\n- The prompt explicitly warns: \"When you cannot determine difficulty from the prompt alone, default to moderate scores (0.5–0.6)\"\n\n### Key Insight: Deceptive Simplicity\n\nThe single biggest classifier failure mode is short prompts that look easy but are actually hard. The Kimi card now has three explicit failure-pattern sections that address this:\n\n1. **DECEPTIVELY SIMPLE PROMPTS**: \"Do not equate prompt brevity with task simplicity.\"\n2. **MULTI-STEP WORKFLOWS WITH FEEDBACK LOOPS**: \"Fails when iterating toward a target\"\n3. **MULTI-SERVICE ORCHESTRATION**: \"Fails on coordinating several interacting services\"\n\nThese patterns emerged from analyzing v6 TB2 misroutes where the classifier gave Kimi high scores on tasks like chess-best-move (short prompt, deep game-tree search required), raman-fitting (simple description, domain expertise needed), and train-fasttext (sounds routine, requires iterative training to threshold).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Cost-Weighted Selector\n\n### Formula\n\n```\nutility(c) = score - α · score^(1+γ) · relative_cost\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `score` is the classifier's predicted success probability for candidate `c`\n- `relative_cost` = `candidate_cost / max_cost_among_candidates`\n- `α` (alpha) = 0.30 — controls how aggressively we favor cheaper models\n- `γ` (gamma) = 2.1 — controls how much the penalty scales with score (penalizes high-score cheap models less)\n\n### Intuition\n\n- When Kimi and Opus both score high (e.g., 0.9 vs 0.95), Kimi wins because cost penalty is small relative to score delta\n- When Opus scores much higher than Kimi (e.g., 0.9 vs 0.3), Opus wins because the raw score difference dominates\n- The non-linear exponent (1+γ) means the cost penalty is proportionally smaller for high-confidence cheap scores\n\n### Tuning History\n\nParameters were tuned via gradient descent on 168 samples (56 fixtures × 3 trials):\n- Started at α=0.23, γ=2.1 → Modal accuracy 69.6%, Unstable 37.5%\n- Tuned to α=0.30, γ=2.1 → Modal accuracy 75.0%, Unstable 25.0%\n\nα=0.30 routes more aggressively to Kimi. The improvement comes from correctly routing clear-cut cheap tasks (log summarization, git recovery, single-service infra) while the γ=2.1 exponent protects against routing uncertain tasks.\n\n### Comparison vs Threshold Selector\n\nThe default threshold selector routes to the cheapest model whose score exceeds a fixed quality threshold. The cost-weighted selector outperforms it because it considers the *relative* scores, not just absolute thresholds. A task where Kimi scores 0.82 and Opus scores 0.85 is very different from one where Kimi scores 0.82 and Opus scores 0.98.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Candidate Registry & Model Cards\n\n### Current Active Candidates\n\n| Model | Provider | Cost (in/out per 1M) | Reasoning | Images |\n|-------|----------|---------------------|-----------|--------|\n| Claude Opus 4.6 | Anthropic | $15 / $75 | High | Full |\n| Kimi K2.5 | Fireworks | $0.6 / $2.5 | None | Basic |\n\nKimi is ~25x cheaper than Opus.\n\n### Card Structure\n\nEach card in `candidates.ts` has:\n```\ncapabilities: what the model can do (images, tool calling, etc.)\nstrengths: categories where it excels, with brief examples\nweaknesses: failure patterns with explanations of WHY it fails\nscore_examples: 15-17 scored task descriptions spanning 0.05–0.95\n```\n\n### Kimi Weakness Categories (Current)\n\nThe Kimi card organizes weaknesses around three meta-patterns:\n\n1. **Deceptive simplicity** — tasks with short prompts hiding deep reasoning\n2. **Multi-step feedback loops** — iterating toward thresholds/convergence\n3. **Multi-service orchestration** — coordinating multiple daemons/services\n\nThen specific weak domains:\n- Algorithms (game-tree search, proofs, spectral fitting, complex regex)\n- ML beyond inference (training to thresholds, architecture recovery, tokenization)\n- Security/forensics (cryptanalysis, exploits, password recovery)\n- Domain-specific science (spectroscopy, molecular biology, nuclear physics)\n- Low-level systems (x86-64, Fortran, C89, COBOL)\n- Graphics/spatial (path tracing, gcode, video frames)\n- Complex build systems (niche compilers, cross-compilation)\n\n### Kimi Strength Categories\n\n- Standard single-service infra (gRPC, Nginx, package hosting)\n- Git operations (recovery, leaked secrets)\n- Standard ML inference (pretrained models, predictions)\n- Data processing (logs, CSV, merging)\n- Code migration (Python 2→3, COBOL modernization)\n- Constraint satisfaction (scheduling, optimization)\n\n### History: Why We Removed MiniMax\n\nMiniMax M2.5 was the original cheap candidate. It hit 403 Forbidden errors from Fireworks (eval org IP allowlist issue). Swapped to Kimi K2.5 which uses the same Fireworks provider but doesn't have the allowlist problem.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Offline Evaluation Framework\n\n### Location & Usage\n\n```bash\ncd apps/scripts\nOPENAI_API_KEY=... npm run router-eval -- \\\n  --fixtures ../../evals/router/headroom-fixtures.jsonl \\\n  --trials 3 \\\n  --concurrency 8 \\\n  --selector cost-weighted\n```\n\n### Fixture Format\n\nEach line in the JSONL fixture file:\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"tb2v6-chess-best-move\",\n  \"expectedPrimary\": \"claude-opus-4-6\",\n  \"signals\": {\n    \"sessionId\": \"uuid\",\n    \"currentUserMessage\": \"The file chess_board.png has...\",\n    \"recentMessages\": [],\n    \"systemInfo\": \"\",\n    \"firstUserMessage\": null,\n    \"conversationSummary\": null,\n    \"recentToolCalls\": [],\n    \"surface\": \"exec\"\n  },\n  \"metadata\": {\"taskId\": \"chess-best-move\", \"source\": \"tb2-v6-misroute\", \"category\": \"algorithms/math\"}\n}\n```\n\nRequired fields: `id`, `signals.sessionId`, `signals.currentUserMessage`, `expectedPrimary`.\n\n### Current Fixture Set\n\n75 fixtures total (48 Opus, 21 Kimi), sourced from:\n- TB2 benchmark tasks with known outcomes\n- Manually labeled based on which model succeeds/fails in practice\n- Categories: algorithms/math, ml/data-science, systems/infra, crypto/security, git/vcs, data-processing, misc\n\n### Metrics Reported\n\n- **Modal accuracy**: What % of fixtures get routed to the correct model (across trials, take the most-common routing decision)\n- **Macro F1**: Harmonic mean of per-class precision and recall\n- **Mean per-trial accuracy**: Average accuracy across individual trial runs\n- **Unstable fixtures**: % of fixtures where the routing decision flips across trials\n- **Per-candidate score σ**: Variance of scores across trials for each model\n- **Confusion matrix**: Rows = ground truth, Cols = predicted primary\n\n### Latest Results (75 fixtures, 3 trials, cost-weighted α=0.30)\n\n```\nModal accuracy: 82.7%\nMacro F1: 0.788\nMean per-trial accuracy: 82.7%\nUnstable fixtures: 10.7%\nOpus score σ: 0.032\nKimi score σ: 0.044\n\nConfusion (truth × pred):\n                    kimi-k2.5    claude-opus-4-6\nkimi-k2.5                 15                  8\nclaude-opus-4-6            5                 47\n```\n\n### Fetching the OpenAI Key for Eval\n\nThe key lives in AWS Secrets Manager:\n- Secret name: `PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY`\n- Region: `us-west-1`\n- Account: `686782615134` (Factory prod)\n\n```bash\naws secretsmanager get-secret-value \\\n  --secret-id PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY \\\n  --region us-west-1 \\\n  --query SecretString --output text\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Production Evaluation (TB2)\n\n### Submitting Router Eval Runs\n\n```bash\ncd apps/cli\nbun scripts/submit-eval.ts \\\n  --run-id router-kimi-card-v2-tb2-fixed \\\n  --template tb2_full \\\n  --model auto \\\n  --branch model-router \\\n  --skip-build  # if binary already uploaded\n```\n\nKey: `--model auto` triggers the router. The binary must be built from the `model-router` branch.\n\n### Production Results (4 runs compared)\n\n| Run | Pass Rate | Opus | Kimi | Classifier | Kimi Pass | Notes |\n|-----|-----------|------|------|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| v3 (alpha30, old prompt) | 68.5% | 89 | 0 | fallback | n/a | No OPENAI_API_KEY → all Opus |\n| v4 (alpha30, old prompt) | 65.2% | 89 | 0 | fallback | n/a | Same issue |\n| v2-fixed (new card) | 63.1% | 63 | 21 | ACTIVE | 76.2% | First successful routed run |\n| v2 (new card, run2) | 58.0% | 88 | 0 | fallback | n/a | Different worker, same key issue |\n\n### Interpreting v2-fixed (the only run with active routing)\n\nOn 84 common tasks:\n- Opus-only baseline: 67.9% (average of v3 + v4)\n- Router (v2-fixed): 63.1%\n- **Quality delta: -4.8pp**\n\nBut this overstates the router's cost:\n- 7 \"pure losses\" (passed on all-Opus, failed with router)\n  - 3 are TRUE MISROUTES (Kimi fail, Opus would pass): fix-code-vulnerability, overfull-hbox, pypi-server\n  - 4 are Opus VARIANCE (routed to Opus but failed anyway): adaptive-rejection-sampler, rstan-to-pystan, torch-pipeline-parallelism, write-compressor\n- 5 \"pure wins\" (failed on all-Opus, passed with router): cancel-async-tasks, dna-assembly, gcode-to-text, query-optimize, sqlite-with-gcov\n- 11 tasks are inherently NOISY (v3 and v4 disagree with each other)\n\n**True misroute cost: 3 tasks = 3.6pp**\n\n### Kimi's Production Performance\n\n21 tasks routed to Kimi, 16 passed (76.2%):\n- Perfect categories: git ops (fix-git), data processing (log-summary, multi-source-data-merger), standard infra (kv-store-grpc, nginx-request-logging), ML inference (hf-model-inference, pytorch-model-cli)\n- Surprising passes: openssl-selfsigned-cert, prove-plus-comm, headless-terminal, sanitize-git-repo\n- Failures: fix-code-vulnerability (security), overfull-hbox (iterative LaTeX), pypi-server (surprising), mteb-retrieve (near-tie scores), torch-tensor-parallelism (distributed ML)\n\n---\n\n## 8. Infrastructure & Deployment\n\n### The OPENAI_API_KEY Propagation Problem\n\nThis was the hardest bug in the entire project. The chain:\n\n```\nEval daemon (Python) → fetches secrets → os.environ[\"OPENAI_API_KEY\"]\n  → executor._build_environment() → os.environ.copy()\n    → subprocess.run(tb.sh, env=env)\n      → tb.sh runs Harbor (uv run harbor)\n        → Harbor Python process has key in os.environ\n          → exec.py reads os.environ → passes as -e flags to docker compose exec\n            → Droid binary inside Docker container reads process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY\n```\n\n**Root cause of failure**: The file `evals/src/droid_terminal_bench/agents_v2/eval_run_config.py` defines `_SECRET_ENV_KEYS` — the list of env vars that get forwarded into the Docker container. On the `dev` branch (where workers run), this was:\n\n```python\n_SECRET_ENV_KEYS = (\"FACTORY_API_KEY\", \"GH_TOKEN\")\n```\n\n`OPENAI_API_KEY` was only added on the `model-router` branch but never merged to `dev`. The fix was:\n\n```python\n_SECRET_ENV_KEYS = (\"FACTORY_API_KEY\", \"GH_TOKEN\", \"OPENAI_API_KEY\")\n```\n\n### Patching Workers\n\nWorkers pull from `dev` branch and won't get model-router changes until merged. To hotfix:\n\n```bash\n# Patch all workers via SSM\nWORKERS=\"i-0deae75894d76c1ec i-01f5eae7ed003e8fc ...\"\naws ssm send-command \\\n  --instance-ids $WORKERS \\\n  --document-name AWS-RunShellScript \\\n  --parameters 'commands=[\"cd /home/ssm-user/repo/factory-mono/evals/src/droid_terminal_bench/agents_v2 && sed -i \\\"s/_SECRET_ENV_KEYS = (\\\\\\\"FACTORY_API_KEY\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"GH_TOKEN\\\\\\\")/_SECRET_ENV_KEYS = (\\\\\\\"FACTORY_API_KEY\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"GH_TOKEN\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"OPENAI_API_KEY\\\\\\\")/\\\" eval_run_config.py\"]' \\\n  --region us-west-1\n```\n\n### Verifying Routing is Active\n\nAfter submitting a run, check the droid logs for routing confirmation:\n\n```bash\n# Find which worker got the job\naws logs tail /factory/eval-workers --region us-west-1 --since 10m --filter-pattern \"Starting eval\"\n\n# Check routing in droid logs via SSM\naws ssm send-command --instance-ids <WORKER_ID> --document-name AWS-RunShellScript \\\n  --parameters 'commands=[\"find /home/ssm-user/repo/factory-mono/evals/jobs/<RUN_DIR> -name droid-log-single.log -exec grep -h \\\"Model-Router\\\" {} \\\\; | head -10\"]' \\\n  --region us-west-1\n```\n\nYou should see `[Model-Router] Routed | Context: {\"value\":{\"modelId\":\"kimi-k2.5\",\"source\":\"gpt-5.4-mini\",...}}` for some tasks. If you only see `OPENAI_API_KEY not set; auto-routing disabled` then the key propagation failed.\n\n### Confirming Key Propagation\n\n```bash\n# Check Harbor process has the key\naws ssm send-command --instance-ids <WORKER_ID> --document-name AWS-RunShellScript \\\n  --parameters 'commands=[\"HARBOR_PID=$(pgrep -f \\\"harbor run.*<RUN_ID>\\\" | head -1) && cat /proc/$HARBOR_PID/environ | tr \\\"\\\\0\\\" \\\"\\\\n\\\" | grep OPENAI\"]' \\\n  --region us-west-1\n```\n\nIf Harbor has it but Docker doesn't → `_SECRET_ENV_KEYS` is missing OPENAI_API_KEY.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Results & Quality Analysis\n\n### Cost/Quality Tradeoff (Production, v2-fixed)\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Tasks routed to Kimi | 25% (21/84) |\n| Kimi pass rate | 76.2% (16/21) |\n| Quality delta vs all-Opus | -4.8pp |\n| True misroute quality cost | -3.6pp (3 tasks) |\n| Cost savings | ~24% of total compute cost |\n| Tasks where Kimi outperformed Opus | 3 (cancel-async-tasks, query-optimize, sqlite-with-gcov) |\n\n### Offline vs Production Comparison\n\n| Metric | Offline (75 fixtures) | Production (84 tasks) |\n|--------|----------------------|----------------------|\n| Accuracy | 82.7% | ~80% (estimated) |\n| Kimi routing % | 26.7% | 25% |\n| Kimi score σ | 0.044 | not measured |\n| Key misroutes | 5/75 Opus→Kimi | 3/21 Kimi failures |\n\nThe offline eval is reasonably predictive of production behavior.\n\n### Inherent Variance\n\nTB2 has significant run-to-run variance. Two identical all-Opus runs (v3 and v4) disagree on 11/84 tasks (13%). This means any quality delta smaller than ~4pp is within noise. The router's -4.8pp delta is at the edge of significance — the 3.6pp from true misroutes is real, the remaining 1.2pp is likely noise.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Known Failure Patterns\n\n### Remaining Misroutes (v2-fixed)\n\n1. **fix-code-vulnerability** → Kimi. The classifier scored it as a standard code fix but it requires security/exploit analysis. The Kimi card does list \"Security/forensics\" as a weakness, but the classifier didn't match the task description to that category.\n\n2. **overfull-hbox** → Kimi. LaTeX repair that requires iterating word substitutions until no overfull warnings. Classified as a grep/test loop (Kimi strength) but it's actually an iterative feedback loop (Kimi weakness).\n\n3. **pypi-server** → Kimi. This is the most surprising — building a PyPI server IS a Kimi strength and it's in our positive fixtures. The failure may be a Kimi variance issue rather than a true misroute.\n\n### Patterns the Classifier Still Misses\n\n- **Iterative threshold tasks disguised as simple edits**: overfull-hbox looks like \"edit text\" but is really \"iterate until a constraint is satisfied\"\n- **Security tasks with innocuous descriptions**: \"fix the vulnerability\" doesn't obviously signal that exploit development knowledge is needed\n- **Near-tie scores**: When Opus and Kimi score within 0.05 of each other (e.g., mteb-retrieve at 0.79 vs 0.78), the routing decision is essentially random\n\n### Classifier Latency Distribution\n\n- Median: 2.3s\n- P90: 3.5s\n- P99: 5.5s\n\nThis is first-turn overhead only — the router caches the decision for subsequent turns in the same session.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Operational Runbook\n\n### Running a Router Eval End-to-End\n\n1. **Make changes** to `candidates.ts` or `prompt.ts`\n2. **Run typecheck**: `npm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/droid-core`\n3. **Run tests**: `npm run test -- --filter=@factory/droid-core`\n4. **Run offline eval**:\n   ```bash\n   cd apps/scripts\n   OPENAI_API_KEY=$(aws secretsmanager get-secret-value --secret-id PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY --region us-west-1 --query SecretString --output text)\n   npx tsx src/router-eval/run.ts --fixtures ../../evals/router/headroom-fixtures.jsonl --trials 3 --concurrency 8 --selector cost-weighted\n   ```\n5. **Commit** if improved\n6. **Ensure workers are patched** (OPENAI_API_KEY in _SECRET_ENV_KEYS)\n7. **Submit TB2 run**:\n   ```bash\n   cd apps/cli\n   bun scripts/submit-eval.ts --run-id <name> --template tb2_full --model auto --branch model-router\n   ```\n8. **Verify routing is active** via SSM/droid logs within 5-10 min of start\n9. **Analyze results** after completion (~3-4 hours)\n\n### Adding New Fixtures\n\nFixtures must have `signals.sessionId` (UUID). Quick template:\n\n```python\nimport json, uuid\nfixture = {\n    \"id\": \"tb2v7-task-name\",\n    \"expectedPrimary\": \"claude-opus-4-6\",  # or \"kimi-k2.5\"\n    \"signals\": {\n        \"sessionId\": str(uuid.uuid4()),\n        \"currentUserMessage\": \"The actual task prompt...\",\n        \"recentMessages\": [],\n        \"systemInfo\": \"\",\n        \"firstUserMessage\": None,\n        \"conversationSummary\": None,\n        \"recentToolCalls\": [],\n        \"surface\": \"exec\"\n    },\n    \"metadata\": {\"taskId\": \"task-name\", \"source\": \"tb2-v7\", \"category\": \"category\"}\n}\n```\n\n### Debugging \"All Opus\" Fallback\n\nIf a production run routes 100% to Opus:\n1. Check droid log for `OPENAI_API_KEY not set; auto-routing disabled`\n2. If present → key propagation failed\n3. Verify Harbor process has key: `cat /proc/<HARBOR_PID>/environ | tr '\\0' '\\n' | grep OPENAI`\n4. If Harbor has it but Docker doesn't → patch `_SECRET_ENV_KEYS` on the worker\n5. Kill the current run, resubmit\n\n### Key AWS Resources\n\n| Resource | Location |\n|----------|----------|\n| OpenAI eval key | `PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY` in us-west-1 |\n| SQS queue | `factory-eval-queue` in us-west-1 |\n| CloudWatch logs | `/factory/eval-workers` in us-west-1 |\n| S3 results | `s3://factory-terminal-bench-shared-dev/jobs/` |\n| Binary uploads | `s3://factory-terminal-bench-shared-dev/binaries/<commit>/` |\n\n### Eval Worker Fleet (as of April 2026)\n\n14 workers: `i-0deae75894d76c1ec`, `i-01f5eae7ed003e8fc`, `i-00041a5e6c7c901a1`, `i-00984bceb710cc5b3`, `i-0c5bfeecdb9c3a94d`, `i-045c865479b067dd8`, `i-085a22da6ed0527f5`, `i-07526c296d2f373d4`, `i-0db00d237f5223f11`, `i-027848771556a9e3e`, `i-022cf73a034e0d7a5`, `i-04f05d12b2e8df98a`, `i-0a7715e24cd355917`, `i-0a6b146d5f039aa33`\n\nPlus 2 dedicated router workers: `i-01f342af9d0c3ec84` (router-eval-worker), `i-09777e0e4542e85a5` (router-eval-v2)\n\n---\n\n## Appendix: Lessons Learned\n\n1. **Don't trust prompt brevity as a difficulty signal.** This was the #1 classifier error pattern. Short prompts often hide the hardest tasks (chess analysis, spectroscopy, formal proofs).\n\n2. **Test env var propagation end-to-end.** The OPENAI_API_KEY bug wasted multiple eval runs. Always verify the key reaches the Docker container before interpreting results.\n\n3. **Offline eval is predictive but optimistic.** Our 82.7% offline accuracy translated to roughly 76% Kimi pass rate in production. The gap comes from real-world tasks being messier than curated fixtures.\n\n4. **Variance is the enemy of measurement.** With 11/84 tasks being inherently noisy (different results between two identical Opus runs), any routing improvement smaller than ~4pp is indistinguishable from noise.\n\n5. **General patterns > specific task lists.** Prompt updates that list specific failure domains (\"COBOL/mainframe: EBCDIC encoding, VSAM handling\") work worse than structural patterns (\"multi-step workflows with feedback loops\"). The classifier generalizes better from patterns.\n\n6. **The cost-weighted selector is strictly better than a threshold.** It respects score differentials, not just absolute values. This prevents routing to Kimi when Opus is only 3% more expensive but 15% more likely to succeed.\n\n7. **Some \"misroutes\" are actually wins.** Three tasks that both Opus baselines failed actually passed on Kimi. The router doesn't just save cost — it occasionally routes to a model that's genuinely better for the specific task.\n",
