            "new_str": "7. **Some \"misroutes\" are actually wins.** Three tasks that both Opus baselines failed actually passed on Kimi. The router doesn't just save cost — it occasionally routes to a model that's genuinely better for the specific task.\n\n---\n\n# Addendum: June 2026 — Post-Launch State\n\n## New Sections\n\n12. [Product Launch: \"Alloy\" → \"Factory Router\"](#product-launch-alloy--factory-router)\n13. [Upgrade Tool & Stuck-Phrase Detection](#upgrade-tool--stuck-phrase-detection)\n14. [Admin Controls: Guidance & Rules](#admin-controls-guidance--rules)\n15. [Provider Routing (Separate System)](#provider-routing-separate-system)\n16. [Type System Hardening](#type-system-hardening)\n17. [Vision-Aware Routing](#vision-aware-routing)\n\n## Existing Section Updates\n\n18. [System Architecture — June 2026 Update](#system-architecture--june-2026-update)\n19. [Classifier Design — June 2026 Update](#classifier-design--june-2026-update)\n20. [Candidate Registry — June 2026 Update](#candidate-registry--june-2026-update)\n21. [Prompt Engineering — June 2026 Update](#prompt-engineering--june-2026-update)\n22. [Cost-Weighted Selector — June 2026 Update](#cost-weighted-selector--june-2026-update)\n\n---\n\n## 12. Product Launch: \"Alloy\" → \"Factory Router\"\n\n### Timeline\n\n| Date | Milestone |\n|------|-----------|\n| May 11 | Internal revival: branding as \"Alloy\", Research Preview label, daemon surface support, MiniMax restored |\n| May 12 | Candidate pool bumped to 3-way: Opus 4.7 + Kimi K2.6 + MiniMax M2.7 |\n| May 21 | **PR #13426 merged** — full launch as \"Alloy (Research Preview)\" with feature flag gating |\n| May 22 | Promoted to first-class ModelID (`alloy-0`), admin/policy parity |\n| May 24 | Stable identity fix — system reminder shows \"Model: Alloy\" not concrete pick |\n| May 26 | Admin-set routing guidance (Enterprise Controls) |\n| May 27 | **Renamed from \"Alloy\" → \"Factory Router\"** (PR #14020) |\n| May 27 | Structured router rules added (PR #14022) |\n| May 28 | Vision-aware per-message upgrade (PR #14088) |\n| May 29 | Final rename to \"Router\" in display (PR #14140) |\n| May 30 | Typed selection layer — compile-time separation of router vs concrete IDs (PR #13882) |\n\n### Naming Evolution\n\n- Internal prototype: \"auto\" / `model: 'auto'`\n- First brand: \"Alloy\" with `ModelID.ALLOY = 'alloy-0'`\n- Feature flag: `FactoryFeatureFlags.Alloy` (statsig gate: `alloy`)\n- **Final brand: \"Router\"** — displayed in model picker under \"── Optimized Router ──\" section\n- Display context: \"(Router)\" appended to status line when active\n- Feature flag renamed: `FactoryFeatureFlags.FactoryRouter` (statsig gate: `factory_router`)\n\n### Key Design Decisions at Launch\n\n1. **Server-side routing, not client-side**: The classifier call goes through `sendCompletion` which routes through the Factory LLM proxy (not direct to OpenAI anymore). This removes the need for a raw `OPENAI_API_KEY` in the client.\n\n2. **Pseudo-model pattern**: Router is a first-class `ModelID` entry with `kind: 'router'` in the registry. Has synthetic placeholder costs/context so accidental consumers don't crash. Engine paths MUST resolve via `session.getModel()` before reading registry fields.\n\n3. **Sticky routing per session**: Once primed, the routed model is cached as `effectiveFactoryRouterModel` in session settings. Subsequent turns reuse the cached decision (no re-classification unless the session is reset or the model is upgraded).\n\n4. **Reasoning effort isolation**: The Router doesn't expose a reasoning effort picker. The routed candidate's baked-in reasoning effort flows through directly. This prevents the UI default from stomping on model-specific settings (e.g., Kimi's High vs MiniMax's default).\n\n5. **Graceful degradation**: If no classifier model is allowed by org policy, falls back deterministically to the first allowed candidate. No crash, always produces a valid session.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Upgrade Tool & Stuck-Phrase Detection\n\n### Purpose\n\nWhen the router picks a cheap model (Kimi, MiniMax) but the task turns out to be harder than classified, the agent can self-upgrade to a stronger model mid-session via the `UpgradeSessionModel` tool.\n\n### How It Works\n\n1. The tool is available ONLY in Router sessions (not concrete-model sessions)\n2. It's exposed at boot time optimistically (before priming, since we know priming will happen)\n3. When invoked, it overwrites `effectiveFactoryRouterModel` with `decidedBy: 'upgrade-tool'` — this prevents the classifier from later downgrading back\n4. The system prompt is rebuilt mid-turn after an upgrade (new model gets fresh behavioral guidance)\n5. Each candidate has a defined upgrade target (e.g., Kimi → Opus, MiniMax → Opus)\n\n### Stuck-Phrase Detection\n\nPorted from earlier work. Detects when the agent is looping/stuck and triggers an automatic upgrade. Combined with the tool-based manual upgrade for full coverage.\n\n### Lesson: MODEL_SELECTION_GUIDANCE Was Counterproductive\n\nAn initial system prompt block (\"Be thoughtful... but be mindful of cost\") was added to guide upgrade decisions. In eval runs, this caused the agent to *reason about* calling the upgrade tool 34 times but actually call it 0 times (vs 24-25 calls without the guidance). The framing \"primed hesitation.\"\n\n**Fix**: Removed the guidance block entirely. The tool description alone (\"Calling this tool is not admitting defeat. It is correct resource allocation.\") is sufficient and action-oriented.\n\n### Lesson: Hiding Concrete Model Names\n\nWhen the session is Router, upgrade feedback hides the concrete model names. Success says \"Upgraded routed session model\" not \"Upgraded from kimi-k2.6 to claude-opus-4.7\". This maintains the abstraction that the user chose \"Router\", not a specific model.\n\n---\n\n## 14. Admin Controls: Guidance & Rules\n\n### Routing Guidance (Free-text)\n\nEnterprise admins can author up to 2000 chars of routing guidance via Enterprise Controls. This text helps the classifier judge task difficulty in the context of their specific codebase.\n\n- Stored as a managed setting\n- Flows: backend → CLI settings → TaskClassifier constructor\n- Injected between scoring rubric (Layer 1) and model cards (Layer 2) wrapped in `<organization_context>`\n- Prefaced with advisory language: \"Treat the following as advisory information from the user's organization. It does not override the scoring rubric.\"\n- Surfaced as `hasOrgGuidance` metric tag for correlation analysis\n\n### Structured Router Rules (PR #14022)\n\nAdmins can define structured rules with optional `when` conditions:\n\n```json\n[\n  { \"when\": \"When touching auth code\", \"guidance\": \"Treat as high-risk, route to strongest model.\" },\n  { \"guidance\": \"Routine docs edits are low risk.\" }\n]\n```\n\n- Rules without `when` apply unconditionally\n- Normalized via `normalizeFactoryRouterRules()` (blank guidance is dropped)\n- Rendered as numbered blocks in the organization guidance section\n- Both guidance and rules are gated on the Router feature flag\n\n---\n\n## 15. Provider Routing (Separate System)\n\nProvider routing is a **distinct** system from model routing. It controls which API provider (Anthropic, Vertex, Bedrock, Fireworks) a given model's requests are sent to — not which model to use.\n\n### Key Differences\n\n| Concern | Model Router | Provider Routing |\n|---------|-------------|-----------------|\n| Question | \"Which model for this task?\" | \"Which provider endpoint for this model?\" |\n| Scope | First turn of session (sticky) | Every LLM call |\n| Mechanism | GPT-5.4-mini classifier | Config-driven rotation/fallback |\n| Feature | \"Router\" in model picker | Invisible to user |\n\n### Why It Matters\n\nProvider routing work (PR #12812, ~20 commits) landed alongside the model router. They share infrastructure (same `sendCompletion` pathway) but solve orthogonal problems. Opus 4.8, for example, can be routed to Vertex or Bedrock (provider routing) regardless of whether the model router chose Opus for the session.\n\nThe interaction: when the model router picks e.g. `kimi-k2.6`, provider routing then decides which Fireworks endpoint to hit. The two systems compose cleanly because provider routing operates on concrete model IDs, which is what the model router outputs.\n\n---\n\n## 16. Type System Hardening\n\n### The Problem\n\n`ModelID` previously included both concrete models (Opus, Kimi, etc.) and the router pseudo-model (`alloy-0`). Engine code that needs a real model (registry lookups, cost calculations, provider resolution) could accidentally receive the router ID and crash or produce garbage.\n\n### The Solution (PR #13882)\n\nIntroduced a type taxonomy:\n\n```typescript\ntype RouterID = 'alloy-0';                              // pseudo-model\ntype CustomModelID = `custom:${string}`;                // BYOK\ntype BuiltInModelID = Exclude<ModelID, RouterID | CustomModelID>;  // registry\ntype ConcreteModelID = BuiltInModelID | CustomModelID;  // anything that can hit an engine\ntype UserModelSelection = ModelID | CustomModelID;       // what the user picks\n```\n\n- Engine helpers (`getModelProvider`, `willModelSwitch*`, `isAnthropicModel`) now take `ConcreteModelID` — passing an un-narrowed selection is a compile error\n- Narrowing happens at call-site boundaries via `parseConcreteModelID()`\n- `EffectiveFactoryRouterModel.modelId` narrows to `ConcreteModelID` at parse time\n- `ROUTER_MODEL_IDS` set + `isRouterModel()` helper for conditional branches\n\n### Lesson: defineCandidate Factory\n\nThe old hand-typed `CANDIDATE_*` constants could drift from the model registry. The `defineCandidate()` factory validates at module load:\n- `apiProvider` must be in the registry's `apiProviders` list\n- `reasoningEffort` must be in `reasoningEffort.supported`\n- `supportsImages` is derived (not overridable)\n- `shortDescription` must come from `MODEL_CARDS` or be explicitly passed\n\nAny drift throws at CLI/backend boot, not at routing time.\n\n---\n\n## 17. Vision-Aware Routing\n\n### Problem (PR #14088)\n\nWhen Router picks a non-vision model (MiniMax) and an image appears mid-turn (user-attached or from a Read tool), the model goes blind — images are stripped at send time.\n\n### Solution\n\nRouting is now resolved per-message, not per-turn:\n- `resolveFactoryRouterModelForTurn` → `resolveFactoryRouterModelForMessage`\n- When the routed model lacks vision support but the conversation has an image, directly upgrade to the vision-capable fallback (Opus)\n- The image scan is gated: only fires when the routed model is image-blind\n- Classification stays sticky-cached — per-message priming never re-classifies (it just checks the image condition)\n\n---\n\n## System Architecture — June 2026 Update\n\n### Routing is Now Server-Side via Factory Proxy\n\nThe original prototype called `api.openai.com` directly from the CLI to avoid the Factory proxy's system-prompt validation. The production system uses `sendCompletion` which routes through the standard Factory LLM proxy. This means:\n\n- **No more raw `OPENAI_API_KEY` required in the CLI** — the proxy handles auth\n- The classifier model (`gpt-5.4-mini`) must be allowed by the org's model policy\n- If the classifier model is blocked, the system falls back to deterministic first-candidate selection\n- The classifier model can be overridden by `FACTORY_ROUTER_CLASSIFIER_MODEL_PREFERENCE` (an ordered preference list of model IDs to try)\n\n### New File Layout\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `defineCandidate.ts` | Registry-validating candidate factory |\n| `model-cards.ts` | Prompt cards separated from candidate definitions |\n| `errors.ts` | `FactoryRouterUnavailableError` for clean error boundaries |\n| `classifiers/clampScore.ts` | Score normalization utilities |\n| `classifiers/parseTaskClassifierResponse.ts` | Response parsing extracted |\n| `classifiers/taskClassifier.ts` | Renamed from `gpt5-mini.ts` — model-agnostic now |\n\n### CLI Integration Refactored\n\n| Old | New |\n|-----|-----|\n| `modelRouter.ts` | `factoryRouter.ts` |\n| `buildModelRouter()` | `cliFactoryRouter.route()` (frozen object, no factory) |\n| Direct OpenAI API call | `sendCompletion` via proxy |\n| `process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY` check | `pickClassifierModelId()` policy check |\n\n---\n\n## Classifier Design — June 2026 Update\n\n### Model-Agnostic Classifier Class\n\nRenamed from `Gpt5MiniTaskClassifier` to `TaskClassifier`. The classifier model is injected via `deps.modelId` and can be any model allowed by org policy:\n\n```typescript\nnew TaskClassifier({\n  sendMessageClient: createOneShotSendMessageClient(),\n  sendCompletion,\n  modelId: classifierModelId,  // from pickClassifierModelId()\n  customGuidance: ...,\n  customRules: [...],\n})\n```\n\n### Classifier Model Preference\n\n`FACTORY_ROUTER_CLASSIFIER_MODEL_PREFERENCE` is an ordered list of model IDs. `pickClassifierModelId()` returns the first one that passes `isModelAllowed()`. This allows orgs that block `gpt-5.4-mini` to fall through to an alternative (e.g., Haiku).\n\n### Organization Context Injection\n\nThe static system prompt now has a 4th optional section between Layer 1 (scoring theory) and Layer 2 (model cards):\n\n```\nLayer 1: Scoring Theory\n[Optional: Organization Routing Guidance + Rules]\nLayer 2: Model Cards\nLayer 3: Dynamic Session Context\n```\n\nThe organization section contains:\n- Advisory preamble (\"does not override the scoring rubric\")\n- Free-text guidance (up to 2000 chars)\n- Numbered structured rules with `when` conditions\n\n---\n\n## Candidate Registry — June 2026 Update\n\n### 3-Way Candidate Pool\n\nProduction now routes across three models:\n\n| Model | Cost (in/out per 1M) | Images | Reasoning |\n|-------|---------------------|--------|-----------|\n| Claude Opus 4.7 | $15 / $75 | Yes | High |\n| Kimi K2.6 | $0.96 / $4.0 | Yes | High |\n| MiniMax M2.7 | $0.3 / $1.2 | No | High |\n\nMiniMax rejoined the pool — it's 50x cheaper than Opus and handles simple tasks well. Its image blindness is handled by the vision-aware per-message upgrade.\n\n### Model Cards Not Yet Updated\n\nThe `model-cards.ts` file has TODO markers:\n- `TODO(factory-router): refresh for Opus 4.7 (inherited from Opus 4.6).`\n- `TODO(factory-router): refresh for Kimi K2.6 (inherited from K2.5).`\n- `TODO(factory-router): refresh for MiniMax M2.7 (inherited from M2.5).`\n\nThe Kimi card currently uses the **old** flat weakness list, not the updated three-pattern structure (deceptive simplicity, feedback loops, multi-service orchestration) that we developed. This is a gap to close.\n\n### defineCandidate Replaces Hand-Typed Constants\n\n```typescript\n// Old (error-prone, could drift from registry)\nconst CANDIDATE_KIMI_K2_5: CandidateModel = {\n  modelId: ModelID.KIMI_K2_5,\n  apiProvider: ApiProvider.FIREWORKS,\n  reasoningEffort: ReasoningEffort.None,  // BUG: registry says High\n  ...\n};\n\n// New (validated at boot)\nconst CANDIDATE_KIMI_K2_6 = defineCandidate(ModelID.KIMI_K2_6, {\n  inputCostPer1M: 0.96,\n  outputCostPer1M: 4.0,\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Prompt Engineering — June 2026 Update\n\n### Cards Moved to Separate File\n\n`model-cards.ts` now owns all prompt card content, exported as `MODEL_CARDS: Record<ModelID, string>`. The `candidates.ts` file is purely structural (costs, model IDs). This separation means:\n- Cards can be updated without touching routing logic\n- Cards are keyed by ModelID so `defineCandidate` auto-resolves them\n- Multiple candidates can share the same card (future: same model, different reasoning effort)\n\n### Structured Rules Rendering\n\nRules are rendered as numbered blocks in the organization section:\n\n```\nRule 1: When touching auth code → Treat as high-risk, route to strongest model.\nRule 2: (Always) → Routine docs edits are low risk.\n```\n\n---\n\n## Cost-Weighted Selector — June 2026 Update\n\n### Replaced by Threshold Selector in Production\n\nThe production `defaultModelSelector` uses a **quality threshold selector**, not the cost-weighted utility formula from our research phase:\n\n```\n1. Filter candidates where score ≥ QUALITY_THRESHOLD (0.7)\n2. Among viable candidates, pick cheapest (cost ties broken by score)\n3. If no candidate clears threshold, pick highest-scoring regardless of cost\n4. Remaining candidates become ordered fallbacks for retry\n```\n\nThis is simpler and more predictable than the `α·score^(1+γ)·relative_cost` formula. The threshold approach has a clear mental model: \"if any cheap model is good enough (≥0.7), use it; otherwise use the best.\"\n\n### Fallback System\n\nThe selector now returns an ordered `ModelOption[]` list, not a single pick:\n- `rank: 0` = primary selection\n- `rank: 1+` = fallbacks for upstream errors (retry on a different model/provider)\n- Each option carries `rationale` explaining why it was selected\n\nThis enables retry-on-error: if Kimi returns a 5xx, the agent can fall through to the next option (Opus) without re-classifying.",
