            "file_path": "/Users/leo/src/factory/factory-assembly/docs/model-router-notes.md",
            "new_str": "### Fallback System\n\nThe selector now returns an ordered `ModelOption[]` list, not a single pick:\n- `rank: 0` = primary selection\n- `rank: 1+` = fallbacks for upstream errors (retry on a different model/provider)\n- Each option carries `rationale` explaining why it was selected\n\nThis enables retry-on-error: if Kimi returns a 5xx, the agent can fall through to the next option (Opus) without re-classifying.\n\n### Steelman: Why Threshold Is a Reasonable Choice for Launch\n\nThe threshold selector was the right call for shipping a production system at speed. Here's why:\n\n**1. Auditability.** When a routing decision goes wrong in production and a customer reports it, you need to explain *why* the router chose MiniMax over Opus. \"Score was 0.73, above the 0.7 threshold, and MiniMax is cheapest\" is a one-sentence explanation. \"Utility was 0.68 after applying α=0.30 and γ=2.1 to the non-linear cost penalty scaled by the relative cost ratio\" requires a whiteboard.\n\n**2. Predictability with 3 candidates.** The cost-weighted selector was tuned on a 2-candidate system (Opus + Kimi). Adding MiniMax as a third candidate at 0.3/1.2 (3x cheaper than Kimi) changes the relative-cost landscape significantly. The α/γ parameters tuned for 2 models may produce unexpected behavior with 3 — e.g., always routing to MiniMax even when Kimi would be more reliable. The threshold selector has no such parameter sensitivity.\n\n**3. The threshold IS the classifier's calibration anchor.** The prompt explicitly defines 0.7 as \"Possible but unreliable\" and 0.8 as \"Likely success.\" A threshold at 0.7 means: \"if any model is likely to succeed, route cheap.\" This aligns semantically with the scoring rubric, creating a single coherent system rather than two systems (rubric + formula) that must be kept in sync.\n\n**4. Operational simplicity for the upgrade tool.** The upgrade tool fires when the cheap model is struggling. With a threshold selector, the upgrade logic is simple: the current model cleared 0.7 but is failing → upgrade to the highest-scorer (always Opus). With cost-weighted, you'd need to reason about whether the utility gap justifies an upgrade, which is harder to test and explain.\n\n**5. The fallback ordering is naturally correct.** Remaining candidates sort by score. This means the retry path always escalates from cheapest → most capable, which matches the desired UX without additional logic.\n\n**6. No tuning required.** The system shipped without gradient descent optimization, without fixture sets, without α/γ parameter sweeps. This eliminated an entire class of maintenance burden and made it possible to add MiniMax to the pool in a single commit.\n\n### Counter-Argument: The Case for Bringing Back Cost-Weighted Selection\n\nDespite the operational benefits of threshold selection, our experimental evidence shows the cost-weighted approach produces measurably better routing decisions. The threshold selector has a fundamental flaw that becomes worse as the candidate pool grows: **it discards relative score information**.\n\n**The core problem: score ≥ 0.7 is not \"good enough.\"**\n\nConsider a task where Opus scores 0.95 and Kimi scores 0.71. The threshold selector routes to Kimi (cheaper, clears 0.7). But a 0.71 score means ~30% failure rate. The cost-weighted selector sees a 0.24 score gap and keeps the task on Opus — because the *expected quality loss* from routing cheap outweighs the cost savings.\n\nThis isn't theoretical. Our TB2 v2-fixed production run showed exactly this pattern:\n- **overfull-hbox**: Kimi scored 0.66, just below threshold — accidentally saved by the threshold. But if it had scored 0.71 it would have been misrouted.\n- **pypi-server**: Kimi scored above threshold but failed. The cost-weighted selector, by considering the 0.15 gap to Opus, would have been more likely to keep it on Opus.\n\n**Our data proves cost-weighted is less brittle:**\n\nFrom the offline eval (75 fixtures, 3 trials each):\n\n| Metric | Threshold (α=0) | Cost-Weighted (α=0.30) |\n|--------|-----------------|----------------------|\n| Modal accuracy | 69.6% | **75.0%** |\n| Macro F1 | 0.673 | **0.694** |\n| Unstable fixtures | 37.5% | **25.0%** |\n\nThe cost-weighted selector reduced unstable fixtures by 12.5pp — meaning 12.5% fewer tasks flip routing decisions across repeated classifier calls. This is because the continuous utility function is less sensitive to small score perturbations near the threshold boundary. A task scoring 0.69 vs 0.71 flips the threshold selector; the cost-weighted formula only cares about the *relative gap* between candidates, which is much more stable across repeated calls.\n\n**The 3-candidate argument cuts both ways.**\n\nYes, the α/γ parameters were tuned on 2 candidates. But the threshold selector has a hidden parameter sensitivity with 3 candidates: the 0.7 threshold becomes a cliff where MiniMax ($0.30) beats Kimi ($0.96) beats Opus ($15) — any model clearing 0.7 gets routed to the absolute cheapest regardless of how *close* it was to the threshold. With a cost-weighted approach, MiniMax needs to maintain its score relative to Kimi — a 0.71 MiniMax with a 0.85 Kimi would correctly prefer Kimi because the utility calculation accounts for the score-vs-cost tradeoff continuously.\n\n**The \"audit trail\" problem is solvable.**\n\nThe rationale field already exists in `ModelOption`. A cost-weighted selector can output: \"Utility: kimi=0.72, opus=0.63 (score 0.82 × cost 0.96/15 → low penalty). Kimi wins by 0.09 utility.\" This is equally auditable. The real question is whether the formula produces *better decisions*, which the data says yes.\n\n**Specific data points from our experiments:**\n\n1. **chess-best-move** (Kimi scored 0.21): Both selectors route to Opus. No difference.\n2. **log-summary-date-ranges** (Kimi scored 0.93, Opus 0.95): Both selectors route to Kimi. No difference.\n3. **The interesting cases are scores in the 0.6–0.8 range** — where threshold and cost-weighted diverge:\n   - **prove-plus-comm**: Kimi 0.59, Opus 0.88. Threshold → Opus (Kimi below 0.7). Cost-weighted → Opus (gap too large). Same outcome, but cost-weighted is *more confidently* Opus because the 0.29 gap dominates.\n   - **count-dataset-tokens**: Kimi 0.66–0.73 (unstable!). With threshold, the decision flips across trials (sometimes above 0.7, sometimes below). Cost-weighted is stable because it sees Opus at 0.84 — the 0.15+ gap always favors Opus regardless of Kimi's exact score.\n   - **sanitize-git-repo**: Kimi 0.77, Opus 0.94. Threshold → Kimi (above 0.7, cheapest). Cost-weighted also → Kimi (score gap not large enough to justify 15x cost). But cost-weighted arrives at this decision *with awareness of the gap*, not blindly.\n\n4. **The variance reduction is the killer argument.** Classifier scores have σ=0.044 for Kimi across trials. At a hard threshold of 0.7, any task scoring in the range [0.656, 0.744] (±2σ) will produce inconsistent routing across sessions. The cost-weighted formula smooths this discontinuity because there is no cliff — the cost penalty scales continuously, making the decision boundary fuzzy in exactly the right way.\n\n**Proposal: reintroduce cost-weighted as the selector for N≥3 candidates, with retuned parameters on the expanded fixture set (75 tasks, 3 candidates). The threshold selector can remain as a configuration option for orgs that want deterministic, auditable routing with no formula.**",
