            "new_str": "## ROUTER-2: Reintroduce cost-weighted selector for 3-candidate pool\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Priority | P2 — Medium |\n| Status | Needs Discussion |\n| Estimate | Medium (1-2 days) |\n| Owner | Leo |\n| Labels | quality, selector |\n\n**Description:**\n\nThe production selector uses a threshold approach: any candidate scoring ≥0.7 enters a pool sorted by cost, cheapest wins. The cost-weighted utility formula (`utility(c) = score - α·score^(1+γ)·relative_cost`) was developed and validated during our prototype but was not included in the launch PR.\n\n**Evidence for cost-weighted (2-candidate eval, 75 fixtures × 3 trials):**\n\n| Metric | Threshold | Cost-Weighted (α=0.30, γ=2.1) | Delta |\n|--------|-----------|-------------------------------|-------|\n| Modal accuracy | 69.6% | 75.0% | +5.4pp |\n| Macro F1 | 0.673 | 0.694 | +0.021 |\n| Unstable fixtures | 37.5% | 25.0% | -12.5pp |\n\n**Why instability matters in production:** Classifier scores have σ=0.044 for Kimi. At threshold 0.7, any task scoring in [0.656, 0.744] (±2σ) randomly flips routing across sessions. This means the *same user with the same prompt* may get Opus one day and Kimi the next. The cost-weighted formula has no cliff — it considers relative gaps, making decisions stable even when absolute scores fluctuate.\n\n**The 3-candidate complication:** α/γ were tuned on Opus+Kimi (2 models). The production pool is Opus ($15) + Kimi ($0.96) + MiniMax ($0.30). The relative_cost ratios change: MiniMax/Opus = 0.02, Kimi/Opus = 0.064. Need to retune α/γ on the 3-candidate fixture set to ensure MiniMax doesn't dominate inappropriately.\n\n**Work required:**\n1. Expand fixture set with `expectedPrimary` labels that include MiniMax-appropriate tasks (simple single-file edits, short Q&A)\n2. Run `optimize-selector.ts` gradient descent on 3-candidate scores\n3. Compare threshold vs cost-weighted on the same 3-candidate offline eval\n4. If cost-weighted wins: ship as new `defaultModelSelector`, keep threshold as a named fallback\n5. Preserve the `ModelOption[]` fallback ordering (this is orthogonal to primary selection)\n\n**Blocked on:** Discussion with Abhay (see Slack thread proposal in notes). The threshold selector's operational simplicity was a valid launch choice; need buy-in before changing a user-facing behavior.\n\n**Key question to resolve:** Should cost-weighted be the default for all orgs, or should it be behind a feature flag / dynamic config so we can A/B test?",
