            "new_str": "## ROUTER-4: CI gate for model card changes (eval harness)\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Priority | P2 — Medium |\n| Status | Backlog |\n| Estimate | Medium (1 day) |\n| Owner | Unassigned |\n| Labels | infra, eval |\n\n**Description:**\n\nThe offline eval harness (`apps/scripts/src/router-eval/run.ts`) exists and works: it takes JSONL fixtures, runs the classifier N trials per fixture, and reports accuracy/F1/instability metrics. The fixture set (`evals/router/headroom-fixtures.jsonl`) has 75 labeled examples. But there is currently no CI enforcement — anyone can edit `model-cards.ts` or `prompt.ts` and ship without measuring the impact.\n\nThis is analogous to shipping a model weights change without running the test suite. The classifier prompt IS the model's \"weights\" for routing decisions.\n\n**Proposed approach:**\n1. Add a GitHub Actions job triggered on changes to `packages/droid-core/src/model-router/model-cards.ts` or `classifiers/prompt.ts`\n2. The job runs `npm run router-eval -- --fixtures evals/router/headroom-fixtures.jsonl --trials 1 --concurrency 8 --json`\n3. Parses the JSON output and fails the PR if modal accuracy drops below a floor (e.g., 80%)\n4. Posts a comment on the PR with the eval summary (accuracy, F1, per-fixture decisions)\n\n**Challenges:**\n- Requires an OpenAI API key in CI. The key `PROD_EVAL_OPENAI_API_KEY` exists in AWS Secrets Manager (us-west-1). Could be injected as a GitHub Actions secret.\n- Single-trial eval has ~10% instability. May want `--trials 2` as a compromise between cost and reliability.\n- Eval takes ~2-3 minutes at concurrency 8 (75 fixtures × 1 trial × 2.3s/call ÷ 8 concurrent = ~22s, plus overhead).\n- The classifier now goes through `sendCompletion` (Factory proxy), not direct OpenAI. The eval harness may need updating to match production's auth pathway.\n\n**Alternative:** Run the eval harness manually before each card PR and include the results in the PR description (lighter weight, no CI infra needed, but relies on human discipline).",
