            "new_str": "## ROUTER-6: Proactive re-classification after first tool response\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Priority | P3 — Low |\n| Status | Backlog |\n| Estimate | Large (2-3 days) |\n| Owner | Unassigned |\n| Labels | quality, architecture |\n\n**Description:**\n\nThe router currently classifies once at session start (first user message) and caches the decision as `effectiveFactoryRouterModel` for the entire session. This is by design — re-classifying every turn would add 2.3s latency per message and defeat prompt caching.\n\nHowever, the #1 misroute pattern is \"deceptive simplicity\": tasks where the user message looks easy but the actual codebase/context is hard. The classifier only sees the user prompt at routing time — it doesn't yet know what the tool calls will reveal. For example:\n- \"Fix the bug\" → classifier sees a simple message → routes Kimi → first Read reveals a 50k-line codebase with complex architecture → Kimi fails\n- \"Set up a server\" → looks standard → routes Kimi → first exec reveals conflicting dependencies requiring orchestration → Kimi struggles\n\nThe upgrade tool is a *reactive* solution (waits for the agent to get stuck, then upgrades). A *proactive* re-classification after the first tool response could catch these cases before failure:\n\n**Proposed approach:**\n1. After the first tool response in a Router session, collect the new signals (tool output, revealed codebase complexity)\n2. Re-run the classifier with the enriched signal set\n3. If the new classification would pick a different (stronger) model AND the score gap exceeds a threshold (e.g., new_opus_score - original_cheap_score > 0.2), silently upgrade\n4. Only fire once per session (not on every tool response)\n\n**Trade-offs:**\n- +2.3s latency on the second turn (classifier call)\n- Additional OpenAI API cost (one extra classifier call per session)\n- Complexity in the session lifecycle (mid-session model switch without user initiation)\n- May conflict with the upgrade tool's logic (both trying to upgrade simultaneously)\n\n**Evidence this would help:** In our TB2 v2-fixed run, 3 of 5 Kimi failures (fix-code-vulnerability, overfull-hbox, pypi-server) would have had stronger Opus scores if the classifier had seen the tool responses revealing the actual task complexity.\n\n**Alternative:** Instead of re-classifying, inject the first tool response summary into the existing classifier signals schema (as `recentToolCalls`) and classify once with richer context. This requires delaying classification until after the first tool call, which changes the latency profile of the first turn.",
