            "new_str": "## ROUTER-7: Validate Kimi K2.6 reasoning effort for routing quality\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Priority | P3 — Low |\n| Status | Backlog |\n| Estimate | Small (half day) |\n| Owner | Unassigned |\n| Labels | quality, eval |\n\n**Description:**\n\nPR #13426 caught a bug where `CANDIDATE_KIMI_K2_5` had `reasoningEffort: None` but the model registry declared Kimi's supported reasoning as `[Off, High]` with default `High`. The `defineCandidate` factory now derives reasoning from the registry, so K2.6 ships with `reasoningEffort: High`.\n\nBut this raises a question we never validated: **is High reasoning the optimal setting for Kimi in a routing context?**\n\nOur original prototype used `reasoningEffort: None` for K2.5. That was a bug relative to the registry, but it also happened to be the configuration under which we collected all our eval data and tuned the model card. The card's scored examples, weakness patterns, and strength categories all reflect Kimi's behavior *without* extended reasoning.\n\n**Questions to answer:**\n1. Does Kimi K2.6 with High reasoning pass tasks that K2.5 with None failed? (i.e., does reasoning actually help for the routing target tasks?)\n2. Does High reasoning significantly increase Kimi's latency or cost? (If Kimi with reasoning takes 30s vs 5s, the cost-per-task savings shrink and Kimi becomes less attractive for the \"quick standard tasks\" category.)\n3. Should the model card be re-evaluated with reasoning=High, or is the existing card's assessment still accurate?\n\n**Work required:**\n- Run a subset of TB2 tasks (the 21 tasks routed to Kimi in v2-fixed) with Kimi K2.6 at both `High` and `Off` reasoning efforts\n- Compare pass rates and latency\n- If Off performs similarly on router-target tasks, consider overriding the registry default to `Off` for the candidate (the `defineCandidate` factory supports explicit `reasoningEffort` override)\n- If High materially improves pass rate, update the model card to reflect the stronger capabilities\n\n**Context:** MiniMax M2.7 also uses High reasoning (registry default). The same question applies there — but MiniMax targets even simpler tasks where reasoning overhead may be pure waste.",
