he 0.7 quality threshold — even on tasks where Kimi would succeed and MiniMax would fail.\n\n**Opus 4.7** — Detailed card inherited from 4.6 with 13 scored examples. Most complete of the three but unvalidated against 4.7's actual capabilities.\n\n## Evidence: Card Quality Directly Impacts Routing Accuracy\n\nDuring our April prototype iteration, we restructured the Kimi card from a flat domain list to a three-pattern failure structure:\n\n1. **DECEPTIVELY SIMPLE PROMPTS** — \"Do not equate prompt brevity with task simplicity. Signals of hidden difficulty include: mathematical/logical reasoning, domain-specific analysis, spatial/visual interpretation, multi-step verification against strict thresholds.\"\n2. **MULTI-STEP WORKFLOWS WITH FEEDBACK LOOPS** — \"Fails when the task requires iterating toward a target (training to accuracy thresholds, tuning parameters until convergence, debugging until a specific test passes).\"\n3. **MULTI-SERVICE ORCHESTRATION** — \"Fails on tasks requiring coordinating several interacting services or daemons.\"\n\nOffline eval results (75 fixtures, 3 trials, same classifier, same selector):\n\n| Metric | Before (flat list) | After (three-pattern) | Delta |\n|--------|-------------------|----------------------|-------|\n| Modal accuracy | 75.0% | **82.7%** | **+7.7pp** |\n| Macro F1 | 0.694 | **0.788** | +0.094 |\n| Unstable fixtures | 25.0% | **10.7%** | **-14.3pp** |\n| Kimi score σ | 0.056 | 0.044 | -0.012 |\n\nThe three-pattern card resolved all top-3 misroute categories from our TB2 v6 analysis:\n- **Algorithms/math** (chess-best-move, raman-fitting, prove-plus-comm): Kimi scores dropped from ~0.55-0.65 to 0.15-0.21\n- **ML beyond inference** (train-fasttext, pytorch-model-recovery): Kimi scores dropped to 0.20-0.30\n- **Complex infra** (qemu-startup, mailman, openssl-cert): Kimi scores dropped to 0.20-0.22\n\nMeanwhile, correct Kimi routes (log-summary, fix-git, pypi-server, cancel-async-tasks) maintained high scores (0.83-0.94).\n\n