            "command": "cat > /tmp/file_linear_tickets.py << 'PYEOF'\nimport json, subprocess, os\n\n# Get LINEAR_API_KEY\nenv_file = \"/Users/leo/src/factory/factory-assembly/.env.local\"\napi_key = None\nif os.path.exists(env_file):\n    for line in open(env_file):\n        if \"LINEAR_API_KEY\" in line and not line.strip().startswith(\"#\"):\n            api_key = line.split(\"=\", 1)[1].strip().strip('\"').replace(\"export \", \"\")\n            break\n\nif not api_key:\n    # Try bashrc\n    import subprocess as sp\n    result = sp.run([\"bash\", \"-c\", \"source ~/.bashrc 2>/dev/null && echo $LINEAR_API_KEY\"], capture_output=True, text=True)\n    api_key = result.stdout.strip()\n\nassert api_key, \"No LINEAR_API_KEY found\"\n\nTEAM_ID = \"a2ed886b-5f39-4c90-b643-2e93af919b03\"  # CL\nPROJECT_ID = \"bd6f9f88-e35f-4ee0-8110-e305028f02ed\"  # Model Router Research Preview\nLEO_ID = \"1d4e45a6-e7f7-4204-8063-5390d595fd87\"\n\ndef create_issue(title, description, priority=2, assignee=LEO_ID):\n    payload = {\n        \"query\": \"mutation($input: IssueCreateInput!) { issueCreate(input: $input) { success issue { identifier title url } } }\",\n        \"variables\": {\n            \"input\": {\n                \"teamId\": TEAM_ID,\n                \"title\": title,\n                \"description\": description,\n                \"priority\": priority,\n                \"projectId\": PROJECT_ID,\n                \"assigneeId\": assignee,\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    result = subprocess.run(\n        [\"curl\", \"-s\", \"-X\", \"POST\", \"https://api.linear.app/graphql\",\n         \"-H\", \"Content-Type: application/json\",\n         \"-H\", f\"Authorization: {api_key}\",\n         \"-d\", json.dumps(payload)],\n        capture_output=True, text=True\n    )\n    resp = json.loads(result.stdout)\n    issue = resp.get(\"data\", {}).get(\"issueCreate\", {})\n    if issue.get(\"success\"):\n        i = issue[\"issue\"]\n        print(f\"  Created: {i['identifier']} — {i['title']}\")\n        print(f\"  URL: {i['url']}\")\n    else:\n        print(f\"  FAILED: {resp}\")\n    return issue\n\n# === Ticket 1: Selector strategy evaluation ===\nprint(\"\\n=== Filing: Selector strategy evaluation ===\")\ncreate_issue(\n    title=\"Evaluate cost-weighted utility selector for 3-candidate pool\",\n    description=\"\"\"## Problem\n\nThe production Router uses a threshold selector: any candidate scoring >= 0.7 enters a cheapest-wins pool. This was the right choice for launch speed but has a fundamental limitation — it discards relative score information between candidates.\n\nWith the 3-candidate pool (Opus $15, Kimi $0.96, MiniMax $0.30), if both MiniMax and Kimi clear 0.7, MiniMax always wins regardless of how much higher Kimi scored. The selector can't express \"MiniMax at 0.71 is not as good as Kimi at 0.85.\"\n\n## Evidence from Prototype\n\nWe validated a cost-weighted utility selector during the April prototype phase:\n\n```\nutility(c) = score - alpha * score^(1+gamma) * relative_cost\nalpha = 0.30, gamma = 2.1\n```\n\nOffline eval results (75 fixtures, 3 trials, same classifier):\n\n| Metric | Threshold | Cost-Weighted | Delta |\n|--------|-----------|--------------|-------|\n| Modal accuracy | 69.6% | **75.0%** | **+5.4pp** |\n| Macro F1 | 0.673 | **0.694** | +0.021 |\n| Unstable fixtures | 37.5% | **25.0%** | **-12.5pp** |\n\nThe instability reduction is the most important: classifier scores have sigma=0.044 per trial. At threshold 0.7, any task scoring in [0.656, 0.744] randomly flips routing across sessions. The cost-weighted formula considers relative gaps between candidates, making decisions stable even when absolute scores fluctuate.\n\n## Caveat\n\nThe alpha/gamma parameters were tuned on a 2-candidate system (Opus + Kimi). The production pool is now 3-way (+ MiniMax). Parameters need retuning on the expanded fixture set.\n\n## Scope\n\n1. Expand fixture set with MiniMax-appropriate tasks (depends on CL-568 card refresh for ground truth)\n2. Run `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/optimize-selector.ts` gradient descent on 3-candidate scores\n3. Compare threshold vs cost-weighted on the same 3-candidate offline eval\n4. If cost-weighted wins: ship behind a dynamic config toggle for A/B measurement\n5. Preserve the `ModelOption[]` fallback ordering (orthogonal to primary selection)\n\n## Approach Decision\n\nShould cost-weighted be default or feature-flagged? Need to discuss with Abhay — this is a behavioral change to a live product. Propose sending a Slack thread with the data before implementation.\n\n## References\n\n- Engineering notes: `docs/model-router-notes.md` (Cost-Weighted Selector section + June update)\n- Eval harness: `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/run.ts`\n- Optimizer: `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/optimize-selector.ts`\n- Prototype branch: `model-router` (commits `114233e627`, `8982c1f168`)\n\"\"\",\n    priority=2,\n    assignee=LEO_ID\n)\n\n# === Ticket 2: Production routing quality observability ===\nprint(\"\\n=== Filing: Production routing quality observability ===\")\ncreate_issue(\n    title=\"Production routing quality observability: dashboards and alerts\",\n    description=\"\"\"## Problem\n\nThe Router is live in production but there is no systematic way to measure or alert on routing quality degradation. The only metrics currently emitted are:\n\n- `routing_decision_count` (counter, tags: classification source, surface, hasOrgGuidance)\n- `routing_classifier_latency` (histogram, same tags)\n\nThese tell us HOW MANY decisions and HOW FAST, but not HOW GOOD. There is no production signal for:\n- Which model was selected per session (no routed_model_id tag)\n- Whether the upgrade tool fired (upgrade tool has ZERO telemetry)\n- Session outcome after routing (pass/fail/abandon)\n- Cost savings realized vs all-Opus baseline\n\n## Why This Matters\n\nIn our TB2 evals, the upgrade tool firing rate was a critical proxy for routing quality:\n- model-shift-v5 (pre-launch): 28% of tasks triggered upgrade (24-25 / 89)\n- alloy-tb2 (with MODEL_SELECTION_GUIDANCE prompt): 0% upgrade rate (0 / 89) — the prompt was suppressing tool usage\n- After removing the guidance: upgrade rate recovered\n\nWithout production telemetry, we would not detect if a prompt change or model update caused the upgrade tool to stop firing (indicating either perfect routing or a suppression regression).\n\n## Proposed Metrics\n\n### Routing Decision Enrichment\nAdd `routed_model_id` tag to existing `routing_decision_count`:\n```typescript\nMetrics.addToCounter(Metric.ROUTING_DECISION_COUNT, 1, {\n  classification: decision.classifierResult.source,\n  surface: signals.surface,\n  hasOrgGuidance: String(hasOrgGuidance),\n  routedModelId: primary.modelId,  // NEW\n});\n```\n\n### Upgrade Tool Telemetry (currently zero instrumentation)\nAdd a counter when the upgrade tool fires:\n```typescript\nMetrics.addToCounter(Metric.ROUTING_UPGRADE_COUNT, 1, {\n  previousModelId: ...,\n  upgradedModelId: ...,\n  surface: ...,\n  reason: 'agent_requested' | 'stuck_phrase',\n});\n```\n\n### Axiom Dashboard Panels\nAdd to the Continuous Learning dashboard (or create a dedicated \"Router Quality\" dashboard):\n1. **Routing distribution** — time series of routed_model_id breakdown (% Opus / % Kimi / % MiniMax)\n2. **Upgrade rate** — upgrades / total Router sessions over time (target: 5-15%, alarm if 0% or >30%)\n3. **Classifier latency P50/P95** — already have the histogram, need dashboard panel\n4. **Cost proxy** — estimated cost savings (sessions on cheap model * cheap_cost / opus_cost)\n5. **Fallback rate** — how often does the classifier fail and we fall back to Opus\n\n### Alerts\n- Upgrade rate = 0 for >24h (possible suppression bug)\n- Upgrade rate > 30% (routing quality degraded, cheap models failing too often)\n- Classifier latency P95 > 8s (classifier may be overloaded)\n- Fallback rate > 10% (classifier reliability issue)\n\n## Files to Modify\n\n- `packages/logging/src/metrics/enums.ts` — add ROUTING_UPGRADE_COUNT\n- `packages/droid-core/src/llms/client/factory-router-routing.ts` — add routedModelId tag\n- `apps/cli/src/tools/executors/client/session-model-upgrade.ts` — add upgrade counter\n- `apps/cli/src/models/sessionModelUpgrade.ts` — add stuck-phrase upgrade counter\n- Axiom dashboard configuration\n\n## References\n\n- Current metrics: `packages/logging/src/metrics/enums.ts` lines 202-204\n- Routing code: `packages/droid-core/src/llms/client/factory-router-routing.ts`\n- Upgrade tool: `apps/cli/src/tools/executors/client/session-model-upgrade.ts`\n- Engineering notes: `docs/model-router-notes.md` (Production Evaluation section)\n\"\"\",\n    priority=1,\n    assignee=LEO_ID\n)\n\n# === Ticket 3: Easy Router evals via existing framework ===\nprint(\"\\n=== Filing: Easy Router evals via existing framework ===\")\ncreate_issue(\n    title=\"Add `tb2_router` eval template for one-command Router quality measurement\",\n    description=\"\"\"## Problem\n\nRunning a Router eval currently requires manual steps:\n1. Ensure binary is built from the correct branch\n2. Remember the exact flags: `--model auto --branch <branch>`\n3. After completion, manually compare against an all-Opus baseline\n4. No standard way to measure cost savings or routing distribution from results\n\nThere is no `tb2_router` template and no standard process for periodic Router quality regression testing.\n\n## Goal\n\nMake it trivial to answer: \"How is Router performing right now vs all-Opus?\" with a single command.\n\n## Proposed Solution\n\n### 1. Add `tb2_router.json` template\n\n```json\n{\n  \"eval_type\": \"terminal-bench-v2\",\n  \"config\": {\n    \"n_concurrent\": 4,\n    \"harbor\": {\n      \"dataset\": \"terminal-bench@2.0\"\n    },\n    \"droid\": {\n      \"model\": \"auto\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nUsage: `bun scripts/submit-eval.ts --run-id router-quality-june --template tb2_router`\n\nNo need to pass `--model auto` manually — the template handles it.\n\n### 2. Add `tb2_router_smoke.json` (quick subset for iteration)\n\nA 10-15 task subset that includes:\n- Tasks that should definitely route to Opus (chess-best-move, password-recovery, feal-cryptanalysis)\n- Tasks that should definitely route cheap (log-summary, fix-git, kv-store-grpc)\n- Borderline tasks that test the selector (overfull-hbox, pypi-server, prove-plus-comm)\n\nThis gives a fast signal (~20 min vs ~4 hours for full) suitable for validating card/selector changes before committing to a full run.\n\n### 3. Router results post-processing script\n\nAdd a script (or extend the existing results tooling) that:\n- Parses session settings files from a completed Router run to extract `providerLock` / `effectiveFactoryRouterModel`\n- Reports routing distribution (% per model)\n- Compares pass rates per-model-routed\n- If a baseline all-Opus run exists, computes quality delta and cost savings\n- Outputs a formatted summary suitable for PR descriptions or Slack\n\n### 4. Document the Router eval workflow\n\nAdd to the `run-evals` skill or a dedicated section in `docs/model-router-notes.md`:\n```\n## Running a Router Eval\n1. Submit: bun scripts/submit-eval.ts --run-id <name> --template tb2_router\n2. Monitor: aws logs tail /factory/eval-workers --follow --region us-west-1\n3. Analyze: bun scripts/router-eval-results.ts --job <job-dir>\n4. Compare: bun scripts/router-eval-results.ts --job <router-job> --baseline <opus-job>\n```\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `tb2_router.json` and `tb2_router_smoke.json` templates exist and work with `submit-eval.ts`\n- [ ] Smoke template includes a balanced mix of easy/hard/borderline tasks (10-15 total)\n- [ ] Results script extracts routing distribution + per-model pass rates from completed jobs\n- [ ] Comparative mode shows quality delta and cost savings vs a baseline run\n- [ ] All of the above documented in a runbook\n\n## References\n\n- Existing templates: `evals/src/eval_queue/templates/`\n- Submit script: `apps/cli/scripts/submit-eval.ts`\n- Offline eval harness (different from TB2): `apps/scripts/src/router-eval/run.ts`\n- Engineering notes: `docs/model-router-notes.md` (Operational Runbook section)\n- Previous manual Router eval runs: `router-kimi-card-v2-tb2-fixed_2026-04-16__23-46-59`\n\"\"\",\n    priority=2,\n    assignee=LEO_ID\n)\n\nprint(\"\\n=== Done ===\")\nPYEOF\n\npython3 /tmp/file_linear_tickets.py",
